We explore the effect of board size on the adoption of AI-skilled
employees, addressing a significant gap in the literature. While much
is known about board size and its effect on firm performance, little
attention has been given to its influence on AI workforce integration. We
address how governance structures shape the ability of firms to adopt
transformative technologies. This is especially important as firms navi-
gate the rapidly changing technological landscape, where agility and
innovation are paramount.
To address the challenge of understanding firms' investments in AI,
we employ data on AI-skilled employees recently developed by Babina
et al. (2024). This dataset leverages cutting-edge textual analysis tech-
niques to identify AI-related roles from resume data, providing a
groundbreaking and precise measure of the AI workforce. Historically,
measuring the extent of AI workforce integration has been challenging
due to the absence of standardized metrics. This novel approach repre-
sents a significant advancement, enabling robust analysis of the factors
influencing AI adoption and shedding light on the dynamics of AI inte-
gration at the firm level.
According to Babina et al. (2024), AI workers are a strong indicator
of a firm’s exposure to and investment in AI, as AI-skilled labor serves as
a critical input for effective AI implementation. While other inputs, such
as data and computing infrastructure, complement AI-skilled human
capital, a human-capital-based measure allows us to assess the relative
intensity of AI investments across firms more effectively. By focusing on
AI-skilled employees, we gain a clearer understanding of the strategic
role human capital plays in driving AI adoption (Babina et al., 2024).
Our results demonstrate that smaller boards play a crucial role in
driving the adoption of AI-skilled employees, a finding that emphasizes
the agility and streamlined decision-making processes inherent to lean
governance structures. Specifically, a reduction in board size by one
standard deviation leads to an 8.4 % increase in the share of AI workers.
This finding highlights that the effect is not only statistically significant
but also carries substantial economic relevance, demonstrating the
meaningful role of board size in shaping AI workforce integration.
Smaller boards are less encumbered by the coordination challenges
and inefficiencies that often arise in larger boards, allowing them to act
swiftly and decisively in dynamic environments. This agility is partic-
ularly important in the context of adopting transformative technologies
like AI, where the ability to integrate specialized talent quickly can be a
key determinant of success. The findings align with prior research
highlighting the strategic advantages of smaller boards in fostering rapid
decision-making and reducing coordination costs (Lipton and Lorsch,
1992; Raheja, 2005; Chatjuthamard et al., 2022; Eisenberg et al., 1998;
Treepongkaruna et al., 2024; Yermack, 1996). Smaller boards are better
equipped to align organizational strategies with the fast-paced demands
of technological innovation, making them an essential element of
effective corporate governance in an AI-driven economy.
The robustness of these findings is reinforced by a suite of rigorous
validation methods. Propensity score matching ensures that the
observed effects are not biased by differences in firm characteristics,
creating comparable treatment and control groups (Lennox et al., 2012;
Rosenbaum and Rubin, 1983). Entropy balancing further strengthens
the analysis by weighting the dataset to achieve near-perfect balance
across covariates, thus eliminating residual biases (Hainmueller, 2012;
Hainmueller and Xu, 2013). Instrumental-variable analysis addresses
endogeneity concerns, confirming that the effect of smaller boards on
increased AI adoption is probably causal rather than correlational. These
methods collectively provide compelling evidence that smaller boards
are a decisive factor in the successful integration of AI talent, consistent
with Babina et al.’s (2024) analysis showing the transformative role of
human capital in AI adoption.
We also explore interactions between board size and firm-specific
attributes, offering deeper insights into the contextual factors that
enhance the effectiveness of smaller boards. For firms with high R&D
intensity, smaller boards excel in fostering innovation by facilitating
