4.3. Empirical strategy and additional variables
We follow the methodology in Babina et al. (2024) and estimate the
following regression analysis:
Δ (Share of AI Workers)2010–2018 =α +β1 (Board Size)2010 +β2 (Con-
trols)2010 +Industry Fixed Effects +ε
To examine the effect of board size on changes in AI workforce
integration, we adopt the empirical approach utilized by Babina et al.
(2024). This method analyzes changes in the dependent variable—the
share of AI workers—from 2010 to 2018, as a function of firm-specific
characteristics measured in 2010. The approach leverages long-term
changes as dependent variables to capture gradual processes like AI
adoption and technological integration, which are not immediately
evident in short-term analyses.
The dependent variable, Δ (Share of AI Workers)2010–2018, represents
the growth in the proportion of AI-skilled employees in a firm over the
eight-year period. Independent variables include firm-level character-
istics such as board size, financial resources, and governance attributes
from 2010. These baseline measures are critical for understanding how
initial conditions influence subsequent adoption of AI technologies and
workforce integration.
This approach offers several distinct advantages. First, it provides a
robust framework for studying long-term effects by focusing on
extended time horizons, which are essential for understanding slow-
moving processes like AI adoption.5 By smoothing out short-term fluc-
tuations, this method isolates enduring trends and reduces noise,
enhancing the clarity and reliability of results (Babina et al., 2024).
Second, the use of initial levels as independent variables mitigates issues
of reverse causality. For instance, changes in the share of AI workers
from 2010 to 2018 cannot influence board size or financial character-
istics of the firm as recorded in 2010, allowing for a clearer causal
interpretation of the relationships. This temporal separation aligns with
theoretical frameworks emphasizing the role of initial resources and
governance structures in shaping long-term strategic outcomes (Babina
