Our empirical strategy incorporates a robust set of control variables
to ensure that the observed effect of board size on changes in the AI
workforce is not confounded by other firm-specific characteristics.
These controls address key factors identified in prior research as influ-
ential in technological adoption and organizational decision-making,
aligning the model with well-established theoretical frameworks.
One key control variable is the percentage of female directors on the
board. Gender diversity has been shown to enhance decision-making
and creativity within boards, which can positively influence strategic
investments such as AI adoption (Adams and Ferreira, 2009; Adams and
Funk, 2012; Almor, Bazel-Shoham and Lee, 2022; Bazel-Shoham et al.,
2024). Diverse boards are often more inclusive and innovative, fostering
a governance environment conducive to exploring emerging technolo-
gies. Similarly, the percentage of independent directors is included to
account for the role of board independence in reducing agency conflicts
and ensuring accountability (Jenwittayaroje and Jiraporn, 2019;
Masulis and Mobbs, 2023; Rosenstein and Wyatt, 1990). Independent
directors, who are less influenced by management, are more likely to
prioritize strategic growth opportunities, such as expanding the AI
workforce.
Firm size is another critical control variable, reflecting the greater
financial and managerial resources available to larger firms. Larger
firms benefit from economies of scale, which often enable them to invest
more readily in cutting-edge technologies like AI (Agrawal et al., 2019).
Profitability captures a firm’s financial health and its capacity to allocate
resources toward high-cost, high-return projects such as AI. Profitable
firms are more likely to take risks on transformative technologies, as
they have the flexibility to pursue long-term innovation strategies
(Cockburn et al., 2018).
Our analysis also includes leverage, measured as the firm’s debt-to-
assets ratio. Firms with higher leverage may face financial constraints,
limiting their ability to invest in AI workforce expansion. Controlling for
leverage ensures that the results are not biased by differences in firms’
financial obligations. Similarly, capital expenditures reflect firms’ in-
vestment priorities, with higher expenditures often indicating a focus on
traditional infrastructure rather than intangible assets like AI-related
human capital (Mihet and Philippon, 2019).
R&D intensity, or research and development expenditures as a per-
centage of assets, is a key indicator of a firm’s commitment to innova-
tion. Firms with higher R&D intensity are typically more inclined to
adopt cutting-edge technologies, making this variable essential for
capturing baseline differences in firms’ innovation capabilities. Adver-
tising spending is included as a control to account for firms that focus
more on market-oriented strategies rather than technological innova-
tion, ensuring that the model distinguishes between different strategic
priorities.
Additional control variables include dividends, which represent cash
outflows to shareholders that could otherwise be allocated to reinvest-
ment in AI, and cash reserves, which indicate a firm’s liquidity and its
ability to fund long-term projects without external financing (Loureiro
et al., 2021). Asset tangibility, measured as the proportion of physical
assets, reflects a firm’s focus on tangible versus intangible investments.
Firms with lower asset tangibility are more likely to prioritize digital
transformation efforts, such as AI integration.
Moreover, the effective tax rate captures the impact of taxation on
firms’ available capital for investment, while the current ratio reflects
short-term liquidity and a firm’s capacity to meet immediate obligations
while investing in AI. Finally, we include industry fixed effects to ac-
count for variation across industries. Together, these control variables
