5.1. Baseline regression analysis
Table 2 examines the effect of board size in 2010 on the subsequent
change in the share of AI-skilled workers from 2010 to 2018, providing
insights into how governance structures influence the adoption of AI
talent. The dependent variable, Δ (Share of AI Workers)2010–2018, mea-
sures the growth in the proportion of AI-skilled employees during the
study period. The independent variable of interest is the natural log of
board size in 2010, with industry-fixed effects included to control for
unobserved heterogeneity across sectors. Standard errors are clustered
by industry to account for correlations within industry-level observa-
tions, ensuring robust inference.
The results reveal a significant negative effect of board size on the
change in AI workforce share. In Model 1, the coefficient for board size is
− 0.105 (p < 0.05), while in Model 2, it is− 0.182 (p < 0.01). These
findings suggest that firms with larger boards in 2010 were slower to
adopt AI talent compared to those with smaller boards. These findings
align with the strategic agility hypothesis, which posits that smaller
boards, by reducing coordination challenges and fostering quicker
decision-making, enable firms to adapt more effectively to technological
innovations like AI. The agility and focused governance associated with
smaller boards appear to be a key factor in the proactive integration of
AI talent, as evidenced by the stronger growth in AI workforce share
among firms with smaller boards.
Conversely, the results challenge the resource advantage hypothesis,
which argues that larger boards provide greater access to expertise and
external networks, facilitating complex transitions like AI adoption.
While larger boards may offer resource benefits in other contexts, their
inefficiencies—such as slower decision-making and difficulty aligning
diverse perspectives—may hinder their ability to respond effectively to
the rapidly evolving demands of AI integration. This demonstrates the
importance of agility in governance structures for technological
adaptation.
