5.2. Propensity score matching (PSM)
To ensure robustness and address endogeneity concerns, propensity
score matching (PSM) is employed in the analysis presented in Table 3.
PSM is a powerful statistical method that creates a comparison group
closely resembling the treatment group in terms of observable charac-
teristics (Lennox et al., 2012; Rosenbaum and Rubin, 1983). By
matching firms with large board sizes (treatment group) to similar firms
with smaller board sizes (control group) based on 13 firm-specific
characteristics (i.e., the 13 control variables in the regression anal-
ysis), PSM enables a robust evaluation of the causal effects of board size
on corporate outcomes. This approach eliminates biases introduced by
differences in observable variables, ensuring that the treatment and
control groups differ only in the factor of interest—board size.8
Table 3 Panel A focuses on comparing the treatment and control
groups before and after matching. Before matching, significant differ-
ences exist between the two groups. Firms with large boards (treatment
group) are generally larger in terms of total assets. These firms also
display greater advertising intensity and yet lower cash reserves
