corporate outcomes between 2010 and 2018. The logic of this approach is that
many governance attributes—such as board size—adjust slowly over time, so
exploiting cross-sectional heterogeneity in the initial period provides a cleaner
identification strategy and mitigates concerns about reverse causality. Consis-
tent with this reasoning, board size in our sample is highly persistent: the mean
natural log of board size is 2.327 in 2010 and 2.355 in 2018. Even after eight
years, the average changes only minimally, demonstrating the stability of board
size and supporting the appropriateness of the long-difference specification.
8 PSM offers several critical advantages. First, it reduces selection bias by
balancing covariates between the treatment and control groups, replicating the
