5.3. Entropy balancing
For further robustness, we implement entropy balancing in Table 4.
Unlike propensity score matching (PSM), which creates a matched
sample by selecting comparable observations, entropy balancing
weights the dataset such that the treatment (large board size) and con-
trol groups are balanced across all observed covariates. This method
ensures that the weighted means of covariates in the treatment and
control groups are identical, addressing any pre-existing differences.
The benefits of entropy balancing are significant. First, it minimizes
data loss, as no observations are discarded during the reweighting pro-
cess, unlike in matching techniques where unmatched units are
excluded. Second, entropy balancing ensures near-perfect covariate
balance, reducing residual bias in the estimates. Third, it avoids the
arbitrariness of selecting matching criteria or thresholds, providing a
more robust and transparent method of achieving balance. This makes
entropy balancing especially useful in cases where sample sizes are
limited or the distributions of covariates differ widely between groups
(Hainmueller, 2012; Hainmueller and Xu, 2013; Tübbicke, 2022).
