5.4. Instrumental-variable analysis (IV)
Table 5 employs instrumental-variable (IV) analysis to further
address potential endogeneity issues in estimating the impact of board
size on changes in the share of AI-skilled workers. Endogeneity may
arise from omitted variable bias, measurement errors, or reverse cau-
sality, which could lead to biased and inconsistent estimations in ordi-
nary least squares (OLS) regressions. IV analysis mitigates these
concerns by using external instruments that are correlated with the
endogenous variable (board size) but uncorrelated with the error term in
the second-stage regression (Angrist and Krueger, 1991). The IV
approach ensures that the estimated effect of board size on AI workforce
adoption reflects a causal effect, not spurious correlations driven by
confounding factors. By leveraging instruments that are plausibly
exogenous, this method strengthens the validity and reliability of the
findings.
Our first instrument is the average board size of firms located in the
same zip code. This choice is justified based on the findings of Knyazeva
et al. (2013), which show that the local supply of directors is critically
important. Firms in close proximity tend to share access to the same pool
of directors, leading to similar board size characteristics. For instance,
