In Model 4, the interaction between board size and cash reserves is
also significant and negative, with a coefficient of− 1.364. This finding
highlights the inefficiency of larger boards in deploying liquidity for
strategic investments, such as AI workforce expansion. Cash reserves
provide firms with the flexibility to invest in transformative projects
without the constraints of external financing. However, larger boards,
due to their slower decision-making processes and potential conflicts
among directors, often fail to capitalize on this advantage. Governance
literature has repeatedly noted that larger boards are prone to diffusion
of responsibility, where decision-making is fragmented and account-
ability is diluted (Lipton and Lorsch, 1992). This organizational inertia
can result in missed opportunities to deploy resources effectively,
particularly in competitive and innovation-driven markets.
Furthermore, the interaction results help clarify which theoretical
channels are more or less likely to explain why smaller boards are
associated with greater AI-workforce adoption. The absence of strong
differential effects across profitability and leverage suggests that the
board-size relationship is not primarily driven by firms’ financial
strength or financial constraints. If the mechanism were largely
financial—i.e., smaller boards simply enabling firms with more re-
sources to invest in AI—we would expect the effect of board size to vary
systematically with these characteristics. Instead, the relatively muted
interactions point away from a purely financial-capacity explanation.
In contrast, the interactions involving R&D intensity and cash
holdings offer insights more consistent with governance-based mecha-
nisms. These characteristics proxy for environments where strategic
decisions must be made quickly (R&D-intensive firms) and where the
firm has the liquidity to act immediately (high-cash firms). The fact that
these interactions are more informative suggests that the board-size
effect is likely operating through differences in coordination effi-
ciency, decisiveness, and responsiveness—key dimensions highlighted
in governance theory (Raheja, 2005; Yermack, 1996; Lipton and Lorsch,
1992). Smaller boards may be better able to mobilize resources rapidly
or support innovation-driven workforce changes, whereas larger boards
may face internal frictions that slow down organizational adaptation.
Taken together, the interaction evidence helps narrow the set of
plausible mechanisms: it indicates that the relationship between board
size and AI adoption is unlikely to be driven by financing constraints or
