5.8. The effect of board size on the variability of the AI workforce
To gain further insights, we also explore the effect of board size on
the variability of the AI workforce. Investigating the effect of board size
on the variability of the AI workforce provides critical insights into how
governance structures influence not only the level but also the stability
of AI integration within firms. Understanding this variability is essential,
as fluctuations in AI workforce composition can reflect a firm's capacity
for adaptation, risk tolerance, and strategic experimentation in the face
of technological changes. Variability also highlights how governance
mechanisms can shape the consistency and predictability of investments
in AI talent over time.
To measure variability, we use two distinct metrics. The first is the
standard deviation of the AI workforce between 2010 and 2018,
capturing the dispersion of AI workforce shares around their mean. The
second measure is the range, defined as the difference between the
maximum and minimum shares of AI workers during the same period.
These metrics provide complementary perspectives on how governance
structures impact both the magnitude and extremes of AI workforce
fluctuations.
The results in Table 9 reveal a statistically significant negative effect
of board size on both measures of variability. Specifically, smaller
boards result in higher standard deviations and wider ranges in AI
workforce shares, indicating that firms with smaller boards experience
greater fluctuations in their AI workforce over time. We confirm the
robustness of the results by employing PSM and entropy balancing in
Table 10 and still obtain consistent results. This finding aligns with the
strategic agility hypothesis, which suggests that smaller boards enable
firms to act more decisively and adaptively in dynamic environments
(Lipton and Lorsch, 1992; Raheja, 2005). Smaller boards may encourage
firms to experiment with different levels of AI workforce integration,
leading to variability as firms refine their strategies and adapt to
changing technological and market conditions.
The observed fluctuations may also reflect the iterative nature of AI
adoption. Babina et al. (2024) highlight that firms often undergo a
process of learning-by-doing when integrating AI technologies, making
incremental adjustments to optimize their use of AI-skilled labor.
Smaller boards, with their streamlined decision-making and greater
agility, may facilitate this experimental approach, resulting in greater
workforce volatility as firms explore and recalibrate their AI strategies.
From this perspective, variability is not inherently negative but may
signal proactive adaptation and innovation.
Additionally, resource dependence theory offers further insights into
these results. Smaller boards, while agile, may also operate with fewer
resources and less stability in external networks compared to larger
boards (Pfeffer and Salancik, 1978). This could lead to periodic scaling
up or down of AI workforce investments as smaller boards respond to
financial or environmental constraints. In contrast, larger boards, with
