smaller boards demonstrate superior resource utilization by effectively
directing liquidity toward strategic investments like AI workforce
expansion. This highlights the role of smaller boards in ensuring that
financial resources are deployed to maximize long-term value creation.
Interactions with board characteristics, such as gender diversity and
independence, suggest that while these attributes enhance governance
quality, they do not significantly alter the relationship between board
size and AI workforce adoption. This reinforces the structural advan-
tages of smaller boards, which inherently promote faster decision-
making and better strategic focus.
Moreover, to deepen our understanding of governance impacts, we
analyze the effect of board size on the variability of AI workforce inte-
gration. Measuring variability through the standard deviation and range
of AI workforce shares from 2010 to 2018, we discover that smaller
boards exhibit greater fluctuations in workforce composition. This
finding supports the strategic agility hypothesis, which posits that
smaller boards promote flexibility, experimentation, and adaptive
learning in rapidly changing environments
From a practical perspective, these findings suggest that firms
seeking to thrive in dynamic and innovation-driven industries should
prioritize smaller boards. Smaller boards allow for quicker decision-
making, clearer accountability, and better alignment with strategic
priorities, particularly in areas like AI adoption and R&D. Firms with
significant liquidity can also benefit from smaller boards by ensuring
that resources are allocated effectively to transformative investments.
These insights highlight the critical role of board size in shaping a firm’s
ability to adapt to technological changes and maintain competitiveness.
Although our sample ends in 2018, the relationship between board
size and AI-related workforce dynamics may change as AI has advanced
rapidly in recent years. As AI tools become more capable and reshape a
wider range of tasks, boards may face more frequent and consequential
decisions about workforce adjustments. In such an environment, smaller
boards could respond even more quickly, potentially amplifying the
patterns we document, though faster adoption may also introduce
greater uncertainty. These considerations help clarify the external val-
idity of our findings and point to the value of examining post-2018 data
in future work.
Future research could also examine whether board-level technolog-
ical expertise enhances the strategic-agility role of smaller boards. For
example, boards with directors who have IT experience or greater
